…that knowing is not always separate from doing.

If action is a sensing mechanism, then some information only exists after interaction.

You can’t fully know:

* how a market will respond until you launch,
* how a person feels until you speak,
* how a golf shot will fly until you swing,
* how a path unfolds until you walk it.

The act itself becomes part of the measurement apparatus.

In physics, observation can affect what is observed. More generally, in life, participation changes the system. You’re not standing outside reality measuring it from a distance—you are embedded within it.

That implies a few things:

* Waiting for complete certainty can prevent access to the very information needed to become certain.
* Exploration is not separate from learning; it is a form of learning.
* Some truths are discoverable only through contact.
* Feedback is often more valuable than prediction.

In language you’ve used before, it resembles “tracer dye.” You inject something into the system and then watch where it flows. The action isn’t just a choice—it’s a probe.

So if action is a sensing mechanism, then courage isn’t merely bravery.

It’s sometimes the willingness to perform an experiment on reality and accept whatever data comes back.